            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="accordion">
                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What is the difference between Electrical and Electronics Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Electrical Engineering primarily focuses on the generation, transmission, and distribution of electrical power and the design of electrical systems and equipment. It deals with larger-scale electrical systems like power grids, motors, and generators. Electronics Engineering, on the other hand, concentrates on smaller-scale electronic circuits, components, and systems that process information and control signals. It involves the design of devices like integrated circuits, microprocessors, and communication systems. Many universities offer combined Electrical and Electronics Engineering programs that cover both areas.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">Is programming knowledge necessary for Electrical Engineers?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Yes, programming knowledge is increasingly important for electrical engineers. Programming skills are essential for embedded systems design, microcontroller programming, automation, simulation, and data analysis. Languages like C/C++, Python, and MATLAB are widely used in the field. Additionally, hardware description languages like VHDL and Verilog are important for digital design and FPGA programming. As the industry moves toward smart systems, IoT, and automation, programming skills give electrical engineers a significant advantage in the job market.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What are the emerging areas in Electrical Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Emerging areas include renewable energy systems (solar, wind, and energy storage), electric vehicles and charging infrastructure, smart grid technologies, IoT and smart devices, power electronics with wide-bandgap semiconductors, quantum computing, neuromorphic computing, and AI hardware. The integration of AI and machine learning with electrical systems is creating new opportunities in predictive maintenance, energy optimization, and autonomous systems. Additionally, fields like biomedical electronics, wearable technology, and sustainable energy solutions are growing rapidly.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">How is the job market for Electrical Engineers in India?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>The job market for electrical engineers in India is robust and growing, with opportunities in power generation and distribution companies, renewable energy firms, electronics manufacturing, telecommunications, automotive industry (especially with the EV revolution), automation, and semiconductor design. Government initiatives like Make in India, Digital India, and the push for renewable energy are creating new opportunities. However, the field is becoming more competitive, and engineers with specialized skills in emerging areas like power electronics, embedded systems, IoT, and renewable energy have better prospects.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What certifications can enhance my employability as an Electrical Engineer?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Valuable certifications include: Professional Engineer (PE) license, Certified Energy Manager (CEM), IEEE certifications in power systems or electronics, PLC Programming certifications (Allen Bradley, Siemens), CCNA for networking professionals, CompTIA A+ for IT hardware, Project Management Professional (PMP), and specialized certifications in areas like MATLAB, LabVIEW, AutoCAD Electrical, or specific microcontroller platforms. Industry-specific certifications in renewable energy, electric vehicles, or industrial automation can also be beneficial depending on your career goals.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">How can I prepare for GATE in Electrical Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>To prepare for GATE in Electrical Engineering: (1) Understand the syllabus thoroughly, (2) Focus on core subjects like Circuit Theory, Electrical Machines, Power Systems, Control Systems, and Signals & Systems, (3) Solve previous years' question papers, (4) Use standard textbooks and reference materials, (5) Join a good coaching program if needed, (6) Create a structured study plan with regular revision, and (7) Take mock tests to improve time management and identify weak areas. Pay special attention to topics with higher weightage like Power Systems and Electrical Machines.</p>
